{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Enforce release-source authorization + version lockstep before publication\n\nRe-anchor the release to the proven OSS pattern (uv model): a single\n`workflow_dispatch`-from-`main` workflow that asserts version-lockstep + ancestry,\nthen **builds and publishes directly** via PyPA Trusted Publishing (OIDC — no\nlong-lived secret, no tag relay), gated on a required-reviewers `pypi` environment\nre-keyed from \"v* tags only\" to \"`main` via dispatch\". The source is reviewed-and-\nlanded `main` **by construction**. (Readiness Finding 1 — verified VALID against\n`release.yml:17-21`, `infra/terraform-github/main.tf:23-101`, `docs/releasing.md`.)\n\n## Why\n\n`main` is constrained to the Gerrit replication deploy key, but `refs/tags/v*` was\ndeliberately left open (`infra/terraform-github/main.tf:23-28`) so a human can push\na `v*` tag to drive PyPI + MCP-registry + GitHub-Release publication\n(`release.yml:17-21`, jobs `build`/`publish`/`github_release`/`mcp_registry`). The\nonly gate anywhere is `if: github.event_name == 'push' && startsWith(github.ref,\n'refs/tags/v')` (release.yml:53/81/116) — nothing checks that the tagged SHA is an\nancestor of (or equal to) reviewed `main`, verifies any Gerrit/CI result for that\nexact SHA, or asserts version consistency. A PEP 740\nattestation would correctly name this repo's workflow but cannot distinguish a tag\non reviewed `main` from a tag on any other commit. Separately, the three version\nvalues (`pyproject.toml:10`, `server.json` top-level and `packages[].version`) are\nkept in lockstep only by a manual runbook (`docs/releasing.md`), so a future\nmismatch would publish disagreeing versions across the PyPI / GitHub-Release / MCP\nchannels with no machine check.\n\n## What\n\nAdopt uv's proven release process and pydantic's pre-build version check, in this\norder of control strength:\n\n- **Primary control — initiate from `main` via `workflow_dispatch` (source reviewed\n  by construction).** Make `workflow_dispatch` the sanctioned release trigger, run\n  from the `main` ref. Because the GitHub mirror's `main` is exactly the\n  Gerrit-reviewed-and-landed history, releasing from `main` guarantees the source is\n  reviewed **by construction** — the same guarantee the wider OSS world gets from\n  \"release only from the protected branch.\" This replaces \"accept whatever commit an\n  arbitrary pushed tag points at,\" which was the actual divergence from consensus.\n- **Version-lockstep, before build (pydantic pattern).** A first job parses the\n  intended version and every manifest and asserts exact equality **before build**:\n  `version_input == project.version == server.json.version ==\n  each server.json.packages[].version`; mismatch fails before build.\n- **Ancestry assertion (belt-and-suspenders).** In the same dispatch job, assert the\n  checked-out `main` HEAD is reachable from `origin/main` via\n  `git merge-base --is-ancestor \"$GITHUB_SHA\" origin/main` (checkout with\n  `fetch-depth: 0` + `git fetch origin main`, since a shallow clone defeats ancestry —\n  the repo documents this at `reconcile-bridge.yml:83-88` and `verify-identity.yaml`\n  already uses `fetch-depth: 0`). With dispatch-from-`main` this is redundant with the\n  ref guard, kept as defense-in-depth.\n- **Build, then publish DIRECTLY via PyPA Trusted Publishing — no tag relay.** The\n  same workflow builds and then publishes using OIDC (`id-token: write`, the existing\n  `pypa/gh-action-pypi-publish` trusted-publishing flow). There is **no** intermediate\n  tag push: a tag pushed by the built-in `GITHUB_TOKEN` would not trigger a downstream\n  workflow anyway (GitHub's anti-recursion rule), so a two-phase relay is avoided\n  entirely, and no PAT / GitHub App secret is introduced.\n- **Human authorization — re-key the `pypi` environment (uv release-gate + PyPA\n  Trusted Publishing).** The `publish` job runs in the `pypi` deployment environment\n  with **required reviewers**, so publication needs a second human's approval. Because\n  the job now runs in the dispatch (`refs/heads/main`) context rather than a tag\n  context, the environment's deployment-ref policy is **re-keyed from \"v* tags only\"\n  to \"`main` via `workflow_dispatch`\"** — an operator-side GitHub setting, **no new\n  secret**. Net effect: \"only `v*` tags may publish\" becomes the stronger \"only a\n  dispatch-from-`main`, reviewer-approved run may publish\".\n- **Tag + GitHub Release created AFTER a successful publish (record only).** Once\n  publish succeeds, the workflow creates the `v*` tag and the GitHub Release for the\n  record/mirror; the tag is an **output**, never a trigger. The MCP job derives the\n  version from the dispatch input (not from a tag).\n- **No raw-tag publish path.** With the environment keyed to dispatch-from-`main`, a\n  hand-pushed `v*` tag cannot reach the `pypi` environment and therefore cannot\n  publish — this eliminates the \"arbitrary pushed tag publishes\" surface that was the\n  original finding, rather than merely gating it.\n- **Testing safely.** Exercise the deliberate-version-mismatch and non-`main`-dispatch\n  failure paths against a staging repo / TestPyPI (or a dry-run publish target), never\n  production PyPI/MCP, so negative tests produce no real publication.\n- **`main.tf` / tag-push restriction stays OUT of scope (unchanged, deliberate).**\n  `main.tf:23-28` documents the `tag_lock` was removed (no viable GitHub tag bypass\n  actor in this mirror topology) and the contract test\n  `tests/unit/test_mirror_lock_terraform.py::test_module_is_main_only_no_tag_lock`\n  codifies \"no tag lock\". We do not restrict *who* can push a tag; publication safety\n  now comes entirely from dispatch-from-`main` + the re-keyed reviewer-gated environment.\n- Record the approved SHA, version, manifest versions, and artifact hashes in release\n  evidence.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `.github/workflows/release.yml` — switch the trigger to `workflow_dispatch` (version\n  input, run from `main`); enforce `github.ref == 'refs/heads/main'`; add the\n  version-lockstep + ancestry checks before build; build then publish directly via the\n  OIDC trusted-publishing flow gated on the re-keyed `pypi` environment; create the\n  `v*` tag + GitHub Release after a successful publish (record only). Remove the\n  `push: tags: v*` publish trigger (it can no longer reach the re-keyed environment).\n- **Operator step (not code):** re-key the `pypi` GitHub environment's deployment-ref\n  policy from \"v* tags only\" to \"`main` via `workflow_dispatch`\", keeping required\n  reviewers on. No new secret (publication stays OIDC trusted-publishing).\n- `infra/terraform-github/main.tf` — **no change** (the deliberate no-tag-lock\n  decision and its contract test stand; see the out-of-scope rationale above).\n- `docs/releasing.md` — document the dispatch-from-`main` process, the version-lockstep\n  invariant, and the required environment reviewers. **Section ownership:** this story\n  owns the \"Release-source authorization\" section; Finding 3 owns the \"Build-once\"\n  section and Finding 4 owns the \"Pinning\" section, so the three concurrent release\n  stories do not overlap-edit the same headings.\n- Out of scope: the build-once / pinning work (Findings 3 and 4 — separate stories\n  that also touch `release.yml`; coordinate ordering per the epic).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] The release is initiated by `workflow_dispatch` (a version input) and the\n  dispatch job enforces it runs from `main` (fails if `github.ref != 'refs/heads/main'`),\n  so the released source is reviewed-and-landed `main` by construction — verified by\n  the workflow definition and a run dispatched from a non-`main` ref failing the guard.\n- [ ] A `version-check` step in the dispatch job asserts `version_input`,\n  `pyproject.toml` version, `server.json` version, and every\n  `server.json.packages[].version` are equal and fails before creating the tag on any\n  mismatch — verified (against a staging/TestPyPI target, never production) by a run\n  where the values deliberately disagree, which exits before the tag is created with a\n  message naming each mismatched source.\n- [ ] The workflow builds and then publishes directly via the OIDC trusted-publishing\n  flow (no intermediate tag push / no relay / no PAT), and creates the `v*` tag +\n  GitHub Release only **after** a successful publish (the tag is an output, not a\n  trigger) — verified by the workflow definition (single `workflow_dispatch` job graph;\n  no `push: tags` publish trigger).\n- [ ] The ancestry assertion (`git merge-base --is-ancestor`, checkout `fetch-depth: 0`\n  + `git fetch origin main`) runs before build — verified (staging target) by a\n  dispatch whose HEAD is not reachable from `origin/main` failing before build, and a\n  normal dispatch-from-`main` passing (proving no shallow-clone false-negative).\n- [ ] A hand-pushed `v*` tag cannot publish (the re-keyed environment is reachable only\n  from a dispatch-from-`main` run) — verified by the absence of a tag-triggered publish\n  path in `release.yml` and by `docs/releasing.md` documenting that publication is\n  dispatch-only.\n- [ ] `docs/releasing.md` documents the dispatch-from-`main` process, the\n  version-lockstep invariant, the environment re-key, and the reviewer requirement.\n- [ ] [operator-attested] The live `pypi` GitHub environment is re-keyed to \"`main` via\n  `workflow_dispatch`\" with required reviewers enabled (attested by a comment naming the\n  environment settings screenshot/URL or an org-admin confirmation).\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass, and the change lands via the\n  Gerrit two-vote gate."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784064210562295001,"uuid":"80d4bccc-43ce-4fb1-9727-bc00872d26ab"}